 Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"英国英格兰賀福爾馬德利","lifeSummary":"Richard de Berney是Sir Henry De Berney的儿子，于大约1215年出生在英国諾福爾可巴尼。他于1240年与Catharine de Aygney在英国諾福爾可迪爾哈姆结婚。他们至少是1个儿子的父母。他去世于大约1268年在英国英格兰諾福爾可巴尼享年55岁。"},"hr":{"about 1215–about 1268":"oko 1215.–oko 1268.","1215–1268":"1215–1268","1219–1256":"1219–1256","1241–1301":"1241–1301","1189–1224":"1189–1224","1241":"1241","1240":"1240.","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1301":"1301","1268":"1268","1256":"1256","about 1215":"oko 1215.","1189":"1189","about 1224":"oko 1224.","about 1268":"oko 1268.","about 1256":"oko 1256.","1219":"1219","about 1241":"oko 1241.","Bramshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Barney, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Barney, Norfolk, Engleska, United Kingdom","Dilham, Norfolk, England":"Dilham, Norfolk, England","Barney, Norfolk, England":"Barney, Norfolk, England","Madley, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Madley, Herefordshire, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"about 1215–about 1268":"okolo 1215–okolo 1268","1215–1268":"1215–1268","1219–1256":"1219–1256","1241–1301":"1241–1301","1189–1224":"1189–1224","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1301":"1301","1268":"1268","1256":"1256","about 1215":"okolo 1215","1189":"1189","about 1224":"okolo 1224","about 1268":"okolo 1268","about 1256":"okolo 1256","1219":"1219","about 1241":"okolo 1241","Bramshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, Anglie","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Anglie","Barney, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Barney, Norfolk, Anglie, United Kingdom","Dilham, Norfolk, England":"Dilham, Norfolk, Anglie","Barney, Norfolk, England":"Barney, Norfolk, Anglie","Madley, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Madley, Herefordshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"about 1215–about 1268":"omkring 1215–omkring 1268","1215–1268":"1215–1268","1219–1256":"1219–1256","1241–1301":"1241–1301","1189–1224":"1189–1224","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1301":"1301","1268":"1268","1256":"1256","about 1215":"omkring 1215","1189":"1189","about 1224":"omkring 1224","about 1268":"omkring 1268","about 1256":"omkring 1256","1219":"1219","about 1241":"omkring 1241","Bramshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Barney, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Barney, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Dilham, Norfolk, England":"Dilham, Norfolk, England","Barney, Norfolk, England":"Barney, Norfolk, England","Madley, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Madley, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1215–about 1268":"circa 1215–circa 1268","1215–1268":"1215–1268","1219–1256":"1219–1256","1241–1301":"1241–1301","1189–1224":"1189–1224","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1301":"1301","1268":"1268","1256":"1256","about 1215":"circa 1215","1189":"1189","about 1224":"circa 1224","about 1268":"circa 1268","about 1256":"circa 1256","1219":"1219","about 1241":"circa 1241","Bramshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Barney, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Barney, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dilham, Norfolk, England":"Dilham, Norfolk, England","Barney, Norfolk, England":"Barney, Norfolk, England","Madley, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Madley, Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1215–about 1268":"about 1215–about 1268","1215–1268":"1215–1268","1219–1256":"1219–1256","1241–1301":"1241–1301","1189–1224":"1189–1224","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1301":"1301","1268":"1268","1256":"1256","about 1215":"about 1215","1189":"1189","about 1224":"about 1224","about 1268":"about 1268","about 1256":"about 1256","1219":"1219","about 1241":"about 1241","Bramshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Barney, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Barney, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Dilham, Norfolk, England":"Dilham, Norfolk, England","Barney, Norfolk, England":"Barney, Norfolk, England","Madley, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Madley, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Berney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Burney  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Biorna</b> ‘son of <i>Biorna</i>’. See   Burney   2 and   McBurney  .","French: from a derivative of the personal name   Bernard   or any other name composed of the ancient Germanic element <i>ber(n)</i> ‘bear’."],"variants":[{"name":"Burney","meanings":["English (northern, of Norman origin): habitational name from Bernay in Eure, France, named with a Gaulish personal name <i>Brenno</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>.","Irish (Antrim) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Biorna</b> ‘son of <i>Biorna</i>’, a Gaelic form of the Old Norse personal name <i>Bjarni</i> (from <i>björn</i> ‘bear cub, warrior’).","English: variant of   Barney  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":0,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":9,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":44,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Richard de Berney was born about 1215, in Barney, Norfolk, England as the son of Sir Henry De Berney. He married Catharine de Aygney in 1240, in Dilham, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1268, in Barney, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 55."},"et":{"about 1215–about 1268":"umbes 1215–umbes 1268","1215–1268":"1215–1268","1219–1256":"1219–1256","1241–1301":"1241–1301","1189–1224":"1189–1224","1241":"1241","12